I am creating an extension, and I have a command setup in my `package.json` file, and when I run it I would like to set a variable that I can access from the following command:

``` js
commands.executeCommand('vscode.previewHtml', uri, 2);
```

So, take this command for example:

``` js
context.subscriptions.push(commands.registerCommand('myExtension.runCommand', () => {
    window['myTestValue'] = 'abc123';

    var uri = Uri.file('somefile.html');
    commands.executeCommand('vscode.previewHtml', uri, 2);
}));
```

And this html:

``` html
<html>
<head>
    <title>Test</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1></h1>
    <script>
        var h1 = document.querySelector('h1');
        h1.innerText = window['myTestValue'];
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

When the command gets run, is there a way for me to set the value in the `ts` file so that my html file can access `myTestValue`?

When I run the command, the `h1` text displays `undefined`.
